### **Project purpose**

GigSwap is a comprehensive and user-friendly Telegram bot designed to cater to both ticket buyers and sellers, offering a seamless and efficient transaction process. Accessible and easy to use, GigSwap allows sellers to list their tickets effortlessly, with clear details including the location, event date, and price. Buyers benefit from a user-friendly interface where they can browse and select from a range of available tickets. 

By facilitating direct interactions between parties, GigSwap not only streamlines the sales process but also greatly reduces the risk of fraudulent activities. This innovative platform ensures a reliable and secure environment for users to exchange tickets, enhancing customer satisfaction and trust in the ticket resale market.

### **Project aim**

With an everincreasing number of concerts being announced in Singapore and the a growing number of online transactions for such tickets, we aim to create a easy-to-use, convenient and new platform to help facilitate such sales, ensuring as many people have access to all the events they wish to attend. 

We have developed GigSwap and its functions with a common goal of simply enhancing the user experience, wether you are a buyer or a seller.

### **User stories**

* As a user and seller, I want to be able to list tickets for sale easily.  
* As a user and seller, I want to be able to view my ticket listings.  
* As a user and seller, I want to be able to manage my listings and be able to delete them.  
* As a user and seller, I want to viewing my tickets at a glance in a neat and orderly way.  
* As a user and buyer, I want to be able to see all available listings easily.  
* As a user and buyer, I want to ensure there are not too many tickets shown at once so it is easy to keep track of available tickets.  
* As a user and buyer, I want to be able to filter tickets so I can find the specific tickets I am looking for.  
* As a user and seller, I wish for a way that my listings do not get lost among the many other listed tickets  
* As a user, I wish to ensure I can find tickets easily for certain events  
* As a user and buyer, I want to have a convenient and easy way to contact the seller of the tickets I am interested in.  
* As a user, when a chat is initiated between the 2 parties, I want to have a simple and efficient way to end the chat once a conclusion has been made.  
* As a user and buyer, I wish to ensure sellers I engage with are trustworthy  
* As a user, I wish that there is a way to build trust within the community to prevent fraudulent activities  
* As a user, I wish to be able to see if a seller has good reviews left by other buyers  
* As a user and seller, I wish that buyers can see any comments and reviews to ensure I am trustworthy  
* As a user, I want to be able to share certain ticket listings with my friends and family  
* As a user and buyer, if I see a good listing, I wish for an easy way to show this listing to others who may be keen  
* As a user and seller, I wish for there to be a way that people can share my listing to gain attention  
* As a user, I wish for people to send and receive a link to a specific listing if I wish to share it

### **Project scope**

	GigSwap utilises the Telegram application as the front-end for users, both buyers and sellers, to interact with each other. This is done using Telegram’s front-end interface.

	We have used a set of backend APIs for communication, push notifications, and management algorithms, all implemented using the Telegram API.

### **How GigSwap is different**

	GigSwap is a telegram bot, where it has a niche function of helping people sell and buy concert tickets. We use rich Telegram features like inline buttons to make interactions smoother and more engaging for users. 

With GigSwap being easy to use and efficient, we hope it serves its purpose in letting more people experience concerts in Singapore.

### **GigSwap features**

Once the user starts a conversation with GigSwap, GigSwap will prompt them with the /start command. From there on, a user can choose to buy or sell tickets.

We have currently integrated several core features to allow GigSwap to be functional. Such features are different based on if a user is a buyer or a seller. These features include:

#### **Features for sellers**

1. ##### **Listing ticket sales**

When a user wishes to put tickets up for sale, they can simply use the /sell command. Sellers will be provided with a efficient, simple and effortless way to list their tickets up for sale. The telegram bot will prompt them with the required details before saving their listing in MongoDB’s database. Such details includes the event name, event date, concert location, ticket category, quantity of tickets and price per ticket.

	This core feature allows sellers to list their concert tickets for sale on GigSwap to ensure the public is aware these tickets are up for sale. We intend to implement this using the Telegram Bot API alongside MongoDB, where sellers can input ticket details through a simple form interface. The bot prompts the seller for each piece of information required, before saving the listing. The data is then stored in MongoDB, allowing buyers to query and view all available tickets. Such a feature will build the foundation of our telegram bot and is essential.

	All details provided by sellers when listing their tickets is saved in a MongoDB collection, which allows for easy information retrieval to ensure the feasibility and usability of many other developments.

1. ##### **Ticket management for sellers** 

	We understand sellers may sometimes have many tickets to keep track of, which is why we allow sellers to easily view and manage all their listings. Hence, we have developed commands to allow for sellers to control their listings.

The commands are namely:

* */mylistings*  
* */delete*

	Such commands will certainly aid the seller’s experience in using GigSwap due to the simplicity in managing their sales. With all the information being such easily accessible for sellers, we are certain they will have little to no trouble with dealing with a multitude of different ticket sales. 

When a seller wishes to be able to see all the ticket listings they have made, they can use the /mylistings command, where GigSwap will display all the tickets that a seller has put up for sale. On the other hand, should a ticket be no longer available or any information was inputted incorrectly, the seller can use /delete to delete the whole listing.

#### **Features for buyers**

1. ##### **Browsing ticket sales**

   For buyers, our main focus is to allow them to view the available listings easily, organised and quickly. Thus, buyers can use the /buy command to view all of the listings made by sellers, for a variety of concerts.  
   	To ensure clarity and prevent any congestion, we have ensured that only 10 listings are shown per page. We allow buyers to navigate through all the listings by clicking through buttons labelled Page 1, Page 2 and so forth. This is a helpful feature in ensuring a smooth and clear interface for buyers to browse.   
   All ticket information retrieved from MongoDB reflects the precise data inputted by sellers, ensuring accuracy and timeliness. Hence, what buyers see is exactly as how sellers have inputted the details. We also ensure each ticket sale is numbered accordingly from the time a listing was made. Thus, earlier listings have a lower number and vice versa.

1. ##### **Anonymous chat room with sellers**

	Whenever a buyer is interested in purchasing tickets, we aimed to make it as convenient and as straightforward for a buyer and seller to interact. GigSwap will provide a button, “Purchase ticket/s” which buyers can click. GigSwap then prompts the buyers to provide the listing number they are interested in. 

	After the buyer indicates the listing they wish to inquire further about, GigSwap is able to perform 3 more functions:

1. Start a chat with the seller  
- We have implemented an anonymous chat system through GigSwap such that messages from the buyer/seller are routed through the bot and to the other user.  
- This allows contact to be made between the buyer and seller for any queries or confirmation. After the chat is started, the buyer/seller can provide their telegram/contact details for the transaction to progress further.  
- We developed this feature to ensure an easy and straightforward way for buyers to contact sellers. With messaged being automatically routed through GigSwap, little effort is required by each party to reach out to one another.  
1. queue system for buyers  
- When more than 1 buyer is interested in a particular listing, we have implemented a queue system for buyers to be able to queue to contact the seller.  
- This feature will take place when a seller is already currently in contact with another buyer.   
- The next buyer in the queue will then be connected to chat with the seller once the current chat between the former buyer and seller has ended.  
- To help sellers cope with multiple buyers being interested in the same listing, we ensure that a seller can only talk to 1 buyer at a time. This helps minimise any confusion through the ticketing transaction process when sellers may have to deal with more than 1 potential buyer.  
1. End the chat with the seller  
- Once a transaction is completed, or either party fails to pull through with the transaction, a user can use the /endchat function in order to end the chat between the buyer and seller.   
- The command ensures that GigSwap is still functional for both parties where buyers can continue browsing and sellers can still find other buyers after an interaction.  
- We ensured this feature would help buyers and sellers have an easy way to end the conversation if the transaction falls through, to ensure sellesrs can continue to talk to other potential buyers.

1. ##### **Filters for ticket listings**

	We understand that not all listings made on GigSwap are of each individual’s preference or want. Thus, we felt it was crucial to implement a filtering function whereby buyers can choose the event they wish to browse tickets for, which prevents an overwhelming number of irrelevant listings for themselves.

	As a buyer uses the /buy command and browses through all the listings, GigSwap prompts the buyer if they wish to “Filter by Event Name”. This function will then prompt the buyer to type the name of the event they wish to look for tickets to purchase.

	We ensured that the filter ignores any capitalisation, in hopes to improve user usability. Once the buyer has keyed in the event they are looking for, GigSwap will then display all listings that contains the event name the buyer is searching for. This feature aims to improve user experience and further facilitate the efficiency and simplicity of using GigSwap.

#### **Extension features**

	In order to improve the credibility and feasibility of GigSwap and to protect its users, we are in the midst of discussing and developing certain other features, which we feel can help safeguard each user’s interests. These features include:

1. ##### **User reviews for sellers**

As a buyer, I wish to purchase tickets from more trustworthy and reliablesellers. This will help increase confidence in sellers that use GigSwap.

Our plan to implement this feature is for at the end of a successful/unsuccessful interaction, buyers are able to leave a rating between 0 and 5 stars to rate their interaction with a seller. After the /endchat command is used, GigSwap prompts the buyer if they would like to provide a review for the seller. Should the buyer wish to do so, GigSwap can then prompt the buyer to ask how many stars they wish to rate the seller.

Such reviews will then be stored into a different MongoDB collection. We aim to implement it such as when a buyer is interested in purchasing tickets after using the “Purchase ticket/s” prompt, GigSwap provides an option for buyers to see if they wish to view the seller’s reviews left by other buyers. There is a ‘View Reviews’ button available as a buyer is browsing through available tickets, where GigSwap will then prompt the buyer of which listing number they would like to view the seller’s reviews.

On top of just leaving how many stars a buyer has, GigSwap will showcase the average star rating from all buyers who have purchased from that seller and was willing to leave a rating. This will make it easy and clear to see how reliable and trustworthy a seller is at a glance. Furthermore, should the seller have many past transactions with buyers, we also ensure there are 10 ratings displayed at once, with buyers being able to navigate through different pages to see all the reviews.

1. ##### **Social sharing**

Sometimes, buyers may wish to share certain listings they come across with other family/friends. Hence, we wish to be able to make this possible by allowing buyers to send particular listings to their friends.

We have implemented this feature by generating a a unique URL for each listing that is made. A ‘Share Listing’ button will be available as buyers are navigating through available listings. Each listing needs a unique identifier to be referenced later. This was done by adding a unique ID to each listing when it's created. The unique ID field needs to be added to each document (listing) in the Tickets collection. This was achieved in the saveListingToDatabase method where each new document is assigned a unique ID before being inserted into the collection. When the button is clicked, GigSwap asks for which listing number the user wishes to share, before generating the unique ID and URL.

 The user will be taken to GigSwap, and the listing is automatically displayed. When the bot receives a /start command with a unique ID, it looks up the corresponding listing in the database and sends the listing details to the user. Buyers can then decide if they wish to purchase the ticket or not. 

This feature will benefit both buyers and sellers as sellers may receive a wider audience who will take note of their listing, and buyers are able to conveniently share a listing which helps increase chances of one coming across suitable tickets for themselves.

### **Tech stack**

#### **Front end: Telegram Interface**

	We envision GigSwap to be usable by all Telegram users, our front end is the Telegram User Interface for users to interact with our bot.

	Within Telegram, users interact with GigSwap through messages and buttons provided by Telegram's API. This interaction includes receiving and sending messages between sellers and buyers, and even the buttons that GigSwap uses to prompts users.

The bot is built as a subclass of TelegramLongPollingBot, enabling GigSwap to continuously poll the Telegram servers for updates so the bot can respond in real-time to any messages and commands.

Furthermore, we used InlineKeyboardMarkup to create buttons that users can click to navigate through pages, filter listings and initiate purchases. These certainly make GigSwap’s interface more user-friendly.

	Due to the nature of telegram bots, we also ensured that we created sufficient commands (/sell, /buy, /mylistings, /delete, /endchat etc.) for front end interaction.

#### **Back end: Telegram API, MongoDB**

	Using Telegram API was a clear choice for us to develop the backend of GigSwap due to it being able to help us handle and manage the bot’s commands. It is readily accessible and by integrating the API, we could allow GigSwap to receive updates and process them.

	Many crucial features we developed, such as navigation and management of ticket listings were made possible with Telegram API. Furthermore, we were provided with a way to handle the receiving/sending of messages and routing them through the bot. Furthermore, we also used Telegram buttons to allow

	MongoDB is the NoSQL database that we implemented into our backend to manage all the data stored from each seller’s listings. We decided to use MongoDB Java driver due to it being accessible and the availability of a free tier. MongoDB is a secure and efficient way for us to be able to store the data and it could be integrated into our telebot.

	MongoDB was connected to our backend code using a ConnectionString and MongoClientSettings. It helped us perform database operations, handle data storage and retrieve such data efficiently. This was needed as a foundation to allow GigSwap to be functional. Furthermore, we developed features such as the management of sellers’ listings and sellers ratings that required updates on the data stored in MongoDB. Overall, it provided a structured way to store and manage data used by GigSwap, enhancing its functionality beyond simple message responses. With the ability to make multiple collections, this made it easy and efficient for us to develop such features due to how a large amount data can be stored and easily retrieved despite having different uses.

### **Software Engineering Practices**

1. #### **Code style**

We established a consistent code style, that includes naming conventions, indentations etc. for when we edit parts of our code. Our purpose of doing so is to make sure our code is readable and managable despite both members of our team working on it separately.

Such consistency facilitates easier code reviews and improves understanding across team members. This shortens the period of time it takes for each member to digest the code, supporting the development of our code.

1. #### **Code review process**

We have implemented a formal code review process, whereby our team members review each other’s codes manually. Whenever one of us works on a different part of the code, we ensure we consult the other member to test and ensure our code runs smoothly and is of the best quality. 

We found that this practice helps us improve our code quality, due to an external perspective on our work, helping us grow and learn together as we develop our code further. This facilitates knowledge sharing and ensures we both adhere to coding standards.

1. #### **GitHub Version Control**

	In order to easily collaborate and develop GigSwap together, we made use of GitHub’s version control system where we can easily branch off the main branch whenever we needed to work on a new feature or debug. We will open a Pull Request when we are ready to merge the branch into our main branch and we each ensure we review the code and perform tests before merging.

This helps us to work together without compromising the usability and deployment f the main branch, which is essential in our team when developing such a Telegram bot together.

### **Software Engineering Principles**

1. #### **Incremental development**

	We ensured that we developed GigSwap by focusing on one feature at a time and in small steps, instead of all at once. Throughout the development process, we prevented any situation where too many different features were being integrated together to help us reduce any risk of large-scale failures. On top of that, this allows us to quickly identify the areas that require debugging or changes to be made.

1. #### **Scalability and performance optimization**

We designed GigSwap with scalability in mind as to handle increasingly large number of users in the future. We ensured our features can are accessible for all users and that they can be modified to be used by a wider variety of people in the future. We develop GigSwap with the mindset of supporting growth of users. For example, we implemented the filter function as to help GigSwap maintain a neat and easily navigable interface for buyers who simply are interested in niche events.

#### 

1. #### **Single responsibility principle**

We designed our code such that each method has a singular purpose meant for a function. We ensured we broke our code into functional methods that all perform a certain task to carry out a specific function. We ensured we kept this principle in mind as to improve our code clarity and make it easier to modify a component of our code.

### **How to Get a MongoDB Atlas Connection String**

#### **Step 1: Sign Up for MongoDB Atlas**

If you don't have an account, sign up at [MongoDB Atlas](https://www.mongodb.com/cloud/atlas/signup).

#### **Step 2: Create a Cluster**

1. **Log In**: Log in to your MongoDB Atlas account.  
1. **Create a Cluster**:  
   * Click on **"Build a Cluster"**.  
   * Choose your cloud provider and region.  
   * Click **"Create Cluster"**. This might take a few minutes.

#### **Step 3: Set Up Your Database**

1. **Access Your Cluster**:  
   * Once your cluster is created, click **"Clusters"** in the left-hand menu.  
   * Click on your cluster's **"Connect"** button.  
1. **Whitelist Your IP Address**:  
   * In the connection dialog, click **"Add IP Address"**.  
   * You can add your current IP address or allow access from anywhere  
1. **Create a Database User**:  
   * In the same dialog, under **"Create a Database User"**, create a username and password for your database.  
   * Make sure to save these credentials securely.

#### **Step 4: Get the Connection String**

1. **Choose a Connection Method**:  
   * In the connection dialog, choose **"Connect your application"**.  
1. **Copy the Connection String**:  
   * Select the latest version of the driver (e.g., `Java`).  
1. Copy the provided connection string. It will look something like this:  
   `mongodb+srv://<username>:<password>@cluster0.mongodb.net/<dbname>?retryWrites=true&w=majority`  
   * Replace `<username>`, `<password>`, and `<dbname>` with your actual database user credentials and database name.

### **Testing methodology**

#### **Testing for suitability**

1. ##### **Cognitive walkthrough**

We evaluated the usability of GigSwap by stimulating how users may interact with the bot, and identify and usability issues along the way. For example, we put ourselves in the position of a seller wanting to list a ticket for sale using GigSwap. We then walk through the process step by step as if we were really a seller and view how efficiently the bot guides us through.

As a result, we could identify certain issues such as unclear instructions and anything that a new user could find difficult to understand or follow. As a result of such testing, we could adapt our code according to our findings.

1. ##### **Survey of potential users**

	As our bot was completed, we chose to conduct a google survey with potential users of GigSwap about their preferences, expectations and satisfaction with GigSwap. We provided a description of our vision for GigSwap and then sent out they survey via our social medias, and waited for responses.

	Some sample questions included:

- How likely are you to use a Telegram bot such as GigSwap for buying/selling concert tickets?  
- What features do you think are the most useful in such a bot  
- How likely are you to trust a Telegram bot for buying or selling concert tickets compared to traditional ticketing platforms?  
- How likely are you to recommend a Telegram bot like GigSwap to friends or colleagues interested in buying or selling concert tickets?

As a result, we were able to collect quantitative data to gauge user interests and decide on any further developments we should consider to improve the usefulness and suitability of GigSwap.

1. ##### **Actual user focus group**

	After we had finished our prototype for GigSwap, we employed user testing with an actual focus group, consisting of friends and family, to help us try interacting with GigSwap and provide their feedback. We tasked them all to try out both buying and selling, and test out the features such as filtering for tickets and deleting their listings. After doing so, we asked each of them to share their experience and how suitable the bot is in handling such actions.

	This helped us to pinpoint any overlooked aspects such as user preference and usability issues, that we took into consideration before adjusting GigSwap using their feedback.

#### **Testing for correctness**

1. ##### **Unit and system testing**

	Unit testing was conducted whereby we abstracted and verified the functionality of individual units of code within our bot. For example, we decided that we would write unit tests for critical functions such as listing tickets, whereby we continuously inputted test cases and tracked our tests to ensure it was saved in our MongoDB database. Furthermore, we also tried multiple scenarios such as valid inputs, to ensure each component does what is intended.

	This method of testing helped us to detect and fix bugs easily, and ensure our front end interacts with the user correctly, and backend code is reliable and works well.

	For unit testing, we wrote several test cases manually, which includes scenarios whereby invalid inputs are used, to ensure that we are able to store the data correctly and ensure GigSwap can be used as intended. We wrote such tests to simulate how a user will navigate GigSwap.

1. ##### **User testing**

	During milestone 2, we conducted unit testing as mentioned above with a focus group. In doing so, we explained what GigSwap does before asking them to attempt acting as a seller and buyer, and explore all the features. 

We told them a few things to look out for, including their initial impression of GigSwap, clarity of prompts/buttons, how easy the bot and its functions are to learn and use and any other functions they think can enhance GigSwap’s usability.

This user testing was conducted for about 20 minutes, giving 10 minutes to act as a seller, and 10 minutes as a buyer. After everything was done, we collated some feedback.

As of milestone 2, these are the summary of some responses we received:

1. There should be way to showcase fewer tickets at once as the message received when using /buy is quite long. This may be difficult and tedious for future users to use as more and more listings are added daily.  
1. Being able to filter for the event name is very helpful, as it helps pinpoint the tickets I am interested in, instead of scrolling through many other listings that I am not keen in purchasing.  
1. The bot should give examples for some questions asked, such as the format of the event date, category type etc. to help the listings look more neat and tidy.  
1. If two users are interested in the same listing, we have to consider how to handle the fact that they both wish to start a chat with the seller. However, the seller can only talk to one buyer at a time

All the feedback was taken into consideration for milestone 2, as seen in how we added features such as page numbers, ensuring each page only displays 10 tickets at a time and even a queue system for buyers to interact with the seller. 

Currently, as we have moved onto milestone 3, we decided to conduct yet another round of user testing, with the same group of people and conducted in the same manner as before. Our rationale for doing so is to ensure that the population we were dealing with was already somewhat familiar with GigSwap and how it works. Thus, after we added new features during milestone 3, we wanted to ensure these features were able to be learnt quickly, showcasing if our users will be able to contirnue using GigSwap as we continuously make further upgrades in the future.

At the end of the 20 minutes given, we received yet another set of feedback, which includes:

1. When I view the ratings of a particular seller, there should be a quick summary of all ratings collected so that I am able to see average ratings before I judge if i should contact the seller.  
1. When I click on the URL provided and am taken to GigSwap, there should easily be a way for me to contact the seller of just that particular listing.

Once again, this feedback was taken into account as we refined such features and the flow of GigSwap.

### **Appendix A: Project Documentation and Thought Process**

1. We read up on the telegram API and MongoDB, and how to implement features into the telegram bot and how to store data into the MongoDB database.  
1. Watched a video on how to connect the Telegram bot to the MongoDB database.  
1. Started out on the telegram bot by creating a bot named “GigSwap” with the telegram handle being @GigSwapBot via the BotFather bot on telegram. Added to the bot’s description, and added the /start, /buy and /sell commands for the bot.  
1. Started out on the code for the Telegram bot to allow users to carry out the basic tasks of listing tickets using /sell and buying tickets using /buy.  
1. Coded the telegram bot to send prompts when the user sends the /start and /sell commands. When the user uses the /sell command, the bot will send a few prompts, which are “Please enter the event name”, “How many tickets do you have?”, “What is the event date?”, “Where is the event located?”, “What is the price per ticket?” and “Thanks\! Your listing has been saved.” at the end.  
1. Ran the code to test if the telegram bot works. The results were that the bot did send the prompts, but sometimes prompted the prompts in a wrong order or sent more than 1 prompt at a time.  
1. Debugged the code and successfully made the bot send the prompts in order and the correct number of times.  
1. Created the MongoDB database with the username and password  
1. Added the MongoDB connection string into the code such that the data sent to the telegram bot can be saved into the database later on.  
1. Added the code for the Telegram bot to be able to save the data that the user sends to the bot in the MongoDB database.   
1. Ran the code to test if the messages that the user sends to the bot after using the /sell command were saved into the MongoDB database.  
1. Ran into a problem with the code, where it says connection timeout.  
1. Researched on the problem, found out after quite some time that it was a problem with the NUS wifi, which made it so that the telegram bot could not connect to the MongoDB database. For some reason, the NUS wifi blocked any connections with the MongoDB database. Tried using a mobile hotspot instead and the code ran afterwards.  
1. Tested the /sell command by saving a few listings into the MongoDB database. The data that the user sends the bot after each prompt was successfully stored in the MongoDB database.  
1. Added a chunk of code to allow the /buy command to allow the bot to list out all the available listings in the MongoDB database.  
1. Ran the code and tested both the /sell and /buy commands. The bot correctly updates the database with a new listing everytime the /sell command was initiated and correctly answered by the user, and also correctly outputs all available listings in the MongoDB database when the user uses the /buy command. If there were no listings, the bot sends “No tickets are currently available for sale.”  
1. The bot now has the basic core features.  
1. Wanted to incorporate a ticket verification system so we read up on how to verify concert tickets.  
1. Found out that this feature was too complicated and hard to implement so we decided not to implement this feature.  
1. We decided that we wanted to allow sellers to be able to manage their listings, and hence, created the /mylistings command through the Bot Father bot.  
1. Added a chunk of code to implement the /mylistings command to allow the users to see all the listings that were created by them. This was done by reading all the listings saved in the MongoDB database.  
1. Ran the code and tested the /mylistings command, and found out that the chunk of text was a little bit too hard to read, so we edited the code to allow the bot to send a more well formatted message to improve user readability.  
1. Realised we needed to number the listings for all the list of listings sent by the bot to the user to allow for ease of coding in the future, as we most likely need to number the listings on the list to be able to make it easier to implement other features in the future.  
1. Added a chunk of code to allow the bot to give the listings numbers in order when sending the list of listings from the MongoDB database.  
1. We decided to create a /delete command through the Bot Father bot to allow sellers to manage their listings by deleting their own listings once they have sold their tickets or decided to take down their listing for whatever reason.  
1. Read up on buttons for the telegram bot so that we could implement buttons in the telegram bot to improve user accessibility.  
1. Added a chunk of code to allow users to delete any of their listing they want to by simply pressing a button below the list of their own listings. The buttons below the list of listings would be “Delete Listing 1”, “Delete Listing 2” and so on. Once pressed, the listing will be deleted from the MongoDB database and the database is updated.  
1. We decided to start implementing the filter listings feature, and decided on the “Filter by event name” button below the list of available listings when a user uses the /buy command for better user accessibility and convenience to filter listings.  
1. Added a chunk of code for users to be able to click the “Filter by event name” button, and then send the event name, which is a chunk of text, to the bot, which then allows the bot to filter through all the available listings in the MongoDB database to match the event name sent by the user, regardless of capitalisation. The bot then sends the filtered listings to the user in a list, which will be numbered, and starts from 1 as well.  
1. Tested this code, and it worked after further debugging.  
1. Realised we needed to add pagination into our telegram bot when it sends any list of listings as when there are too many listings, the listing message the bot sends can be very long.   
1. Added a chunk of code to allow the bot to only send 10 listings per page, numbered from 1-10.  
1. Tested the code, and with further debugging, managed to successfully make it work.  
1. Started working on the feature to allow users to actually buy the tickets when they are interested in a listing, by first communicating with the user who listed that particular listing.  
1. Added a chunk of code to add a “Purchase ticket/s” button below the available listings list when the buyer uses the /buy command or when the bot sends the list of filtered listings after the buyer has filtered the listings. The bot will prompt the user “Which listing number are you interested in?” and the user has to type the listing number they are interested in. The listing number accepted will be in accordance to the listing numbers on the specific page the buyer is on, regardless whether it is page 1 or 2 of the available listings, or the filtered listings.  
1. Tested the code and with further debugging, allowed for the button to work.  
1. To complete this feature, we read up on how to connect two users through the telegram bot so that they are able to send messages to each other. We found out that we could do this using the chatID which can be saved in the MongoDB database to route messages from each user, through the bot, to the other user.  
1. Added a chunk of code to allow the buyer to “connect” to the seller of the listing they are interested in through the bot to communicate anonymously when the buyer has typed in the listing number after clicking the purchase ticket button.   
1. Tested the code and it successfully allowed each user to send messages to each other through the bot. However, we found out that there needs to be a command to end the chat between the buyer and seller, or they will forever be connected.  
1. Added a /endchat command through the Bot Father.  
1. Added a chunk of code to allow the /endchat command to end the chat between the seller and buyer by disconnecting the bot from both chatIDs and stop the routing of messages from each user.  
1. Tested the code, but when either users use the /endchat command, the bot just routes the same “/endchat” text to the other user, and any further messages are still routed to the other user.  
1. Debugged the code such that the /endchat command finally works and disconnects the buyer and seller from the chat and does not route messages to each other from either user anymore.  
1. Thought of further features we could implement for milestone 3 to make up for the ticket verification feature that we have decided not to implement.  
1. Upon further thinking, we thought of it from our perspective. When we wanted to purchase concert tickets with our friends, we would usually send each other the listing via a link, which brings them to the listing page. We thought that we could do that with GigSwap as well, to enhance user experience by allowing users to share the listings on GigSwap with their friends, which also allows for more users to know about GigSwap and hence, use the telegram bot to purchase tickets, increasing the number of users.  
1. Hence, we came up with a new feature for users to be able to send a specific listing to their friends via a link, which allows the user who clicks the link to be brought directly to the chat between the user and GigSwap, and receive a message from the GigSwap bot, which contains details of the concert and allows the user to purchase the ticket and contact the seller through the bot’s chat system.   
1. Came up with the code that allows for the GigSwap bot the create a link.  
1. However, upon clicking the link, the user was just brought to the GigSwap chat and nothing happens.  
1. Found out that to implement this feature, we had to create a uniqueID for each listing. Hence, all the previous listings that were on the database could not be used to test the “share listing” feature.  
1. Deleted all the previous listings that were available on the database.  
1. Made it such that when a user uses /sell to list a concert ticket listing, the listing that is saved on the MongoDB database would also include a UniqueID.  
1. With this uniqueID, we made it such that the link generated by the GigSwap bot to a particular listing would prompt the bot to retrieve the listing with that uniqueID from the database, and send it to the user’s chat.  
1. Tested it out, and with further debugging, made it work.  
1. Added a “purchase ticket/s” button below the listing that was sent to the user, to allow the user to purchase the ticket as well. This increases user usability.  
1. Upon further research, we also found out that users are more likely to purchase tickets from sellers that are more credible. For example, on carousell, buyers tend to look at the seller’s star rating before making a decision whether or not to purchase an item. Usually, if the seller has a high star rating, buyers would be more inclined to purchase the item as they would think that the seller is less likely to scam them. Hence, we decided to implement the user rating feature.  
1. For this, we realised that we had to create an entirely new collection on the MongoDB database.  
1. We created the new collection and named it “reviews”  
1. We wanted to create a word based review from buyers to give the seller a review.  
1. However, thinking about it further, this would make it such that buyers may also not be inclined to leave a review, as buyers may be lazy to type a proper review for the seller. Furthermore, word reviews make it such that when a buyer requests to see all the seller reviews, it will be very wordy and hard to read.  
1. Hence, we made it such that the reviews are star rating based, such that users can just type a number from 1-5.  
1. To do this, we made it such that each review left would include the buyer and seller ID in the MongoDB database, and also the star rating.   
1. Hence, we coded it such that when a user requests to see a listing’s seller’s reviews, the bot will retrieve the listing details from the listing collection, which then allows it to check for the seller’s ID. From this, the bot will then check the reviews database and send all the reviews related to the seller’s ID and send it to the buyer.  
1. With many hours of coding and debugging, we managed to make it work, such that after the chat between the buyer and seller ends, the buyer can leave a review for the seller.  
1. However, we realised that even if a buyer does not purchase the tickets from the seller, the buyer would still have to leave a review.  
1. Hence, we changed it such that after the /endchat command was executed between the buyer and seller, a message from the bot will prompt the buyer whether or not the buyer would like to leave a review for the seller. In this way, it would make more sense such that chats that do not end in a deal would not require a review rating.  
1. However, with just the star rating number out of 5, and with so many reviews, buyers would find it hard to see the overall rating of the seller. Hence, we decided that a overall rating was crucial to have for every seller.   
1. Thus, we coded it such that the seller’s overall rating will be the total sum of ratings from all the reviews, divided by the total number of reviews. With this overall rating, the buyers can have a better sense of the seller’s overall reviews from all the buyers who have bought from the seller before.  
1. With all these features implemented, we decided to do a full test of the bot to ensure all features are working as intended.  
1. Bot was tested and all the features worked perfectly as intended.
